 lives in the fishing village of Senya Beraku—where there are no more fish—were like. Asking how these men find meaning in their experiences, Lucht addresses broader existential questions surrounding the lives of economic refugees and their death-defying struggle for a life worth living. He also considers the ramifications of the many deaths that occur in the desert and the sea for those who are left behind.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFisherszGhanaxEconomic conditions. 0aGhanaianszItalyzNaplesxSocial conditions. 0aImmigrantszItalyzNaplesxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aafrican immigrants.  aanthropology and immigration.  acultural studies.  adangerous adventure.  adesert journey.  aemigration and immigration stories.  aethnic demographic studies.  aeuropean anthropology.  aeuropean history.  aeuropean immigration.  aghana immigrants.  aglobalization theory.  ahardships of immigration.  ahigh seas journey.  aimmigrant workers.  aimmigration journey.  ainspiring immigration stories.  ainternational migrants.  ajourney to italy.  amigration to europe.  aovercoming adversity.  arefugee journey.  arefugees and asylees.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027071840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095046740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520950467423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520950467/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY